# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: perlin-noise
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In mathematics, a **fractal** is a geometric shape containing detailed structure at arbitrarily small scales, usually having a fractal dimension strictly exceeding the topological dimension.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Many fractals appear similar at various scales, as illustrated in successive magnifications of the Mandelbrot set.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] This exhibition of similar patterns at increasingly smaller scales is called self-similarity, also known as expanding symmetry or unfolding symmetry; if this replication is exactly the same at every scale, as in the Menger sponge, the shape is called affine self-similar.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fractal geometry relates to the mathematical branch of measure theory by their Hausdorff dimension.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] One way that fractals are different from other geometric figures is how they scale.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Doubling the edge lengths of a filled polygon multiplies its area by four, which is two (the ratio of the new to the old side length) raised to the power of two (the conventional dimension of the filled polygon).
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Likewise, if the radius of a filled sphere is doubled, its volume scales by eight, which is two (the ratio of the new to the old radius) to the power of three (the conventional dimension of the filled sphere).
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] However, if a fractal's one-dimensional lengths are all doubled, the spatial content of the fractal scales by a power that is not necessarily an integer and is in general greater than its conventional dimension.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] This power is called the fractal dimension of the geometric object, to distinguish it from the conventional dimension (which is formally called the topological dimension).
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Analytically, many fractals are nowhere differentiable.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] An infinite fractal curve can be conceived of as winding through space differently from an ordinary line – although it is still topologically 1-dimensional, its fractal dimension indicates that it locally fills space more efficiently than an ordinary line.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] There is some disagreement among mathematicians about how the concept of a fractal should be formally defined.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Mandelbrot himself summarized it as "beautiful, damn hard, increasingly useful.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The consensus among mathematicians is that theoretical fractals are infinitely self-similar iterated and detailed mathematical constructs, of which many examples have been formulated and studied.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fractals are not limited to geometric patterns, but can also describe processes in time.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fractal patterns with various degrees of self-similarity have been rendered or studied in visual, physical, and aural media and found in nature, technology, art, and architecture.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fractals are of particular relevance in the field of chaos theory because they show up in the geometric depictions of most chaotic processes (typically either as attractors or as boundaries between basins of attraction).
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The term "fractal" was coined by the mathematician Benoît Mandelbrot in 1975.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Mandelbrot based it on the Latin *frāctus*, meaning "broken" or "fractured", and used it to extend the concept of theoretical fractional dimensions to geometric patterns in nature.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The word "fractal" often has different connotations for mathematicians and the general public, where the public is more likely to be familiar with fractal art than the mathematical concept.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The mathematical concept is difficult to define formally, even for mathematicians, but key features can be understood with a little mathematical background.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The feature of "self-similarity", for instance, is easily understood by analogy to zooming in with a lens or other device that zooms in on digital images to uncover finer, previously invisible, new structure.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] If this is done on fractals, however, no new detail appears; nothing changes and the same pattern repeats over and over, or for some fractals, nearly the same pattern reappears over and over.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Self-similarity itself is not necessarily counter-intuitive (e.g., people have pondered self-similarity informally such as in the infinite regress in parallel mirrors or the homunculus, the little man inside the head of the little man inside the head ...).
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The difference for fractals is that the pattern reproduced must be detailed.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] This idea of being detailed relates to another feature that can be understood without much mathematical background: Having a fractal dimension greater than its topological dimension, for instance, refers to how a fractal scales compared to how geometric shapes are usually perceived.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] A straight line, for instance, is conventionally understood to be one-dimensional; if such a figure is rep-tiled into pieces each 1/3 the length of the original, then there are always three equal pieces.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] A solid square is understood to be two-dimensional; if such a figure is rep-tiled into pieces each scaled down by a factor of 1/3 in both dimensions, there are a total of 32 = 9 pieces.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] We see that for ordinary self-similar objects, being n-dimensional means that when it is rep-tiled into pieces each scaled down by a scale-factor of 1/*r*, there are a total of *r**n* pieces.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] It can be rep-tiled into four sub-copies, each scaled down by a scale-factor of 1/3.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] So, strictly by analogy, we can consider the "dimension" of the Koch curve as being the unique real number *D* that satisfies 3*D* = 4.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] This number is called the *fractal dimension* of the Koch curve; it is not the conventionally perceived dimension of a curve.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In general, a key property of fractals is that the fractal dimension differs from the *conventionally understood* dimension (formally called the topological dimension).
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] This also leads to understanding a third feature, that fractals as mathematical equations are "nowhere differentiable".
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In a concrete sense, this means fractals cannot be measured in traditional ways.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The result is that one must need infinite tape to perfectly cover the entire curve, i.e. the snowflake has an infinite perimeter.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The history of fractals traces a path from chiefly theoretical studies to modern applications in computer graphics, with several notable people contributing canonical fractal forms along the way.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] A common theme in traditional African architecture is the use of fractal scaling, whereby small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] According to Pickover, the mathematics behind fractals began to take shape in the 17th century when the mathematician and philosopher Gottfried Leibniz pondered recursive self-similarity (although he made the mistake of thinking that only the straight line was self-similar in this sense).
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In his writings, Leibniz used the term "fractional exponents", but lamented that "Geometry" did not yet know of them.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Indeed, according to various historical accounts, after that point few mathematicians tackled the issues and the work of those who did remained obscured largely because of resistance to such unfamiliar emerging concepts, which were sometimes referred to as mathematical "monsters".
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In addition, the quotient difference becomes arbitrarily large as the summation index increases.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Not long after that, in 1883, Georg Cantor, who attended lectures by Weierstrass, published examples of subsets of the real line known as Cantor sets, which had unusual properties and are now recognized as fractals.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Also in the last part of that century, Felix Klein and Henri Poincaré introduced a category of fractal that has come to be called "self-inverse" fractals.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] One of the next milestones came in 1904, when Helge von Koch, extending ideas of Poincaré and dissatisfied with Weierstrass's abstract and analytic definition, gave a more geometric definition including hand-drawn images of a similar function, which is now called the Koch snowflake.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Another milestone came a decade later in 1915, when Wacław Sierpiński constructed his famous triangle then, one year later, his carpet.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Very shortly after that work was submitted, by March 1918, Felix Hausdorff expanded the definition of "dimension", significantly for the evolution of the definition of fractals, to allow for sets to have non-integer dimensions.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The idea of self-similar curves was taken further by Paul Lévy, who, in his 1938 paper *Plane or Space Curves and Surfaces Consisting of Parts Similar to the Whole*, described a new fractal curve, the Lévy C curve.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] That changed, however, in the 1960s, when Benoit Mandelbrot started writing about self-similarity in papers such as *How Long Is the Coast of Britain?
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Statistical Self-Similarity and Fractional Dimension*, which built on earlier work by Lewis Fry Richardson.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In 1975, Mandelbrot solidified hundreds of years of thought and mathematical development in coining the word "fractal" and illustrated his mathematical definition with striking computer-constructed visualizations.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] These images, such as of his canonical Mandelbrot set, captured the popular imagination; many of them were based on recursion, leading to the popular meaning of the term "fractal".
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In 1980, Loren Carpenter gave a presentation at the SIGGRAPH where he introduced his software for generating and rendering fractally generated landscapes.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] One often cited description that Mandelbrot published to describe geometric fractals is "a rough or fragmented geometric shape that can be split into parts, each of which is (at least approximately) a reduced-size copy of the whole"; this is generally helpful but limited.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Authors disagree on the exact definition of *fractal*, but most usually elaborate on the basic ideas of self-similarity and the unusual relationship fractals have with the space they are embedded in.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] One point agreed on is that fractal patterns are characterized by fractal dimensions, but whereas these numbers quantify complexity (i.e., changing detail with changing scale), they neither uniquely describe nor specify details of how to construct particular fractal patterns.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In 1975 when Mandelbrot coined the word "fractal", he did so to denote an object whose Hausdorff–Besicovitch dimension is greater than its topological dimension.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] However, this requirement is not met by space-filling curves such as the Hilbert curve.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Because of the trouble involved in finding one definition for fractals, some argue that fractals should not be strictly defined at all.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] As a group, these criteria form guidelines for excluding certain cases, such as those that may be self-similar without having other typically fractal features.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] A straight line, for instance, is self-similar but not fractal because it lacks detail, and is easily described in Euclidean language without a need for recursion.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] When Mandelbrot introduced the term fractal, he excluded magnification range as a defining characteristic in order to accommodate physical fractals with more limited ranges than their mathematical counterparts.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Images of fractals can be created by fractal generating programs.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Because of the butterfly effect, a small change in a single variable can have an unpredictable outcome.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fractal patterns have been modeled extensively, albeit within a range of scales rather than infinitely, owing to the practical limits of physical time and space.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Models may simulate theoretical fractals or natural phenomena with fractal features.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The outputs of the modelling process may be highly artistic renderings, outputs for investigation, or benchmarks for fractal analysis.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Some specific applications of fractals to technology are listed elsewhere.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Images and other outputs of modelling are normally referred to as being "fractals" even if they do not have strictly fractal characteristics, such as when it is possible to zoom into a region of the fractal image that does not exhibit any fractal properties.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Also, these may include calculation or display artifacts which are not characteristics of true fractals.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Modeled fractals may be sounds, digital images, electrochemical patterns, circadian rhythms, etc.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fractal patterns have been reconstructed in physical 3-dimensional space and virtually, often called "in silico" modeling.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Models of fractals are generally created using fractal-generating software that implements techniques such as those outlined above.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] As one illustration, trees, ferns, cells of the nervous system, blood and lung vasculature, and other branching patterns in nature can be modeled on a computer by using recursive algorithms and L-systems techniques.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The recursive nature of some patterns is obvious in certain examples—a branch from a tree or a frond from a fern is a miniature replica of the whole: not identical, but similar in nature.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Similarly, random fractals have been used to describe/create many highly irregular real-world objects, such as coastlines and mountains.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] A limitation of modeling fractals is that resemblance of a fractal model to a natural phenomenon does not prove that the phenomenon being modeled is formed by a process similar to the modeling algorithms.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Approximate fractals found in nature display self-similarity over extended, but finite, scale ranges.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The connection between fractals and leaves, for instance, is currently being used to determine how much carbon is contained in trees.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fractals often appear in the realm of living organisms where they arise through branching processes and other complex pattern formation.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Richard Taylor and co-workers have shown that the dendritic branches of neurons form fractal patterns.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Ian Wong and co-workers have shown that migrating cells can form fractals by clustering and branching.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Nerve cells function through processes at the cell surface, with phenomena that are enhanced by largely increasing the surface to volume ratio.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] As a consequence nerve cells often are found to form into fractal patterns.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] These processes are crucial in cell physiology and different pathologies.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Multiple subcellular structures also are found to assemble into fractals.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Diego Krapf has shown that through branching processes the actin filaments in human cells assemble into fractal patterns.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Similarly Matthias Weiss showed that the endoplasmic reticulum displays fractal features.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] The current understanding is that fractals are ubiquitous in cell biology, from proteins, to organelles, to whole cells.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Since 1999 numerous scientific groups have performed fractal analysis on over 50 paintings created by Jackson Pollock by pouring paint directly onto horizontal canvasses, see for example.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In 2015, fractal analysis was used to achieve a 93% success rate in distinguishing real from imitation Pollocks.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] A 2024 study used an artificial intelligence technique based on fractals to achieve a 99% success rate.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Decalcomania, a technique used by artists such as Max Ernst, can produce fractal-like patterns.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] It involves pressing paint between two surfaces and pulling them apart.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Cyberneticist Ron Eglash has suggested that fractal geometry and mathematics are prevalent in African art, games, divination, trade, and architecture.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Circular houses appear in circles of circles, rectangular houses in rectangles of rectangles, and so on.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Such scaling patterns can also be found in African textiles, sculpture, and even cornrow hairstyles.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Hokky Situngkir also suggested the similar properties in Indonesian traditional art, batik, and ornaments found in traditional houses.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Ethnomathematician Ron Eglash has discussed the planned layout of Benin city using fractals as the basis, not only in the city itself and the villages but even in the rooms of houses.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] He commented that "When Europeans first came to Africa, they considered the architecture very disorganised and thus primitive.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] In a 1996 interview with Michael Silverblatt, David Foster Wallace explained that the structure of the first draft of *Infinite Jest* he gave to his editor Michael Pietsch was inspired by fractals, specifically the Sierpinski triangle (a.k.a.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Sierpinski gasket), but that the edited novel is "more like a lopsided Sierpinsky Gasket".
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Escher, such as Circle Limit III, contain shapes repeated to infinity that become smaller and smaller as they get near to the edges, in a pattern that would always look the same if zoomed in.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Biophilic fractals are patterns designed to induce the health and well-being benefits associated with exposure to nature's scenery.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] These include stress-reduction and enhanced cognitive capacity.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Designers and architects incorporate biophilic fractals into the built environment to counter the fact that people spend 92% of their time indoors and away from nature's scenery.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fractal fluency is a neuroscience model that proposes that, through exposure to nature's fractal scenery, people's visual systems have adapted to efficiently process fractals with ease.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] This adaptation occurs at many stages of the visual system, from the way people's eyes move to which regions of the brain get activated.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Fluency puts the viewer in a 'comfort zone' so inducing an aesthetic experience.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Neuroscience experiments have shown that Jackson Pollock's fractal paintings induce the same positive physiological responses in the observer as nature's fractals and mathematical fractals.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] This shows that fractal expressionism is related to fractal fluency by providing motivation for artists, such as Pollock, to use Fractal Expressionism in their art to appeal to people.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] Humans appear to be especially well-adapted to processing fractal patterns with fractal dimension between 1.3 and 1.5.
[src:perlin-noise/fractal] When humans view fractal patterns with fractal dimensions in this range, these fractals reduce physiological stress and boost cognitive abilities.
[src:perlin-noise/gradient-noise] The first known implementation of a gradient noise function was Perlin noise, credited to Ken Perlin, who published the description of it in 1985.
[src:perlin-noise/gradient-noise] Later developments were Simplex noise and OpenSimplex noise.
[src:perlin-noise/ken-perlin] He holds a BA. degree in Theoretical Mathematics from Harvard University (1979), a MS degree in computer science from the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences, New York University (1984), and a PhD degree in computer science from the same institution (1986).
[src:perlin-noise/ken-perlin] His research interests include graphics, animation, multimedia, and science education.
[src:perlin-noise/ken-perlin] He developed or was involved with the development of techniques such as Perlin noise, real-time interactive character animation, and computer-user interfaces.
[src:perlin-noise/ken-perlin] He is best known for the development of Perlin noise and Simplex noise, both of which are algorithms for realistic-looking Gradient noise.
[src:perlin-noise/ken-perlin] He is a collaborator of the World Building Institute.
[src:perlin-noise/ken-perlin] In 1996, Perlin received an Academy Award for Technical Achievement from the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, for the development of Perlin noise.
[src:perlin-noise/ken-perlin] He had introduced this technique with the goal to produce natural-appearing textures on computer-generated surfaces for motion picture visual effects, while working on the Walt Disney Productions' 1982 feature film *Tron* for which he had developed a large part of the software.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Ken Perlin developed Perlin noise in 1982 as a result of his problems with the "machine-like" look of computer-generated imagery (CGI) at the time.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] He formally described his findings in a SIGGRAPH paper in 1985 called "An Image Synthesizer".
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] He developed it after working on Disney's computer animated sci-fi motion picture *Tron* (1982) for the animation company Mathematical Applications Group (MAGI).
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Perlin did not apply for any patents on the algorithm, but in 2001 he was granted a patent for the use of 3D+ implementations of simplex noise for texture synthesis.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Simplex noise has the same purpose of Perlin noise, but uses a simpler space-filling grid and produces less grid-shaped artifacts.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Perlin noise is a procedural texture primitive, a type of gradient noise used by visual effects artists to increase the appearance of realism in computer graphics.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] The function has a pseudo-random appearance that causes all details created to stay the same size.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] This property allows it to be controllable; multiple scaled copies of Perlin noise can be inserted into mathematical expressions to create various procedural textures.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Synthetic textures using Perlin noise are often used in CGI to make computer-generated visual elements appear more natural, by imitating the controlled random appearance of textures in nature.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] It is also frequently used to generate textures when memory is limited, such as in demos.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Its successors, such as fractal noise and simplex noise, have became popular in graphics processing units both for real-time graphics and for non-real-time procedural textures in computer graphics.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] It is also frequently used in video games to make procedurally generated terrain that looks natural.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Perlin noise is most commonly implemented as a two-, three- or four-dimensional function, but can be defined for any number of dimensions.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] An implementation typically involves three steps: defining a grid of random gradient vectors, computing the dot product between the gradient vectors and their offsets, and interpolation between these values.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Define an n-dimensional grid where each grid intersection has associated with it a fixed random n-dimensional unit-length gradient vector, except in the one dimensional case where the gradients are random scalars between −1 and 1.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] To work out the value of any candidate point, the unique grid cell in which the point lies is found.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] The 2*n* corners of that cell and their associated gradient vectors is identified.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] For each corner, an offset vector (a displacement vector from that corner to the candidate point) is calculated, and the dot product between its gradient vector and the offset vector is computed.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] This dot product will be zero if the candidate point is exactly at the grid corner.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] For a point in a two-dimensional grid, this requires the computation of four offset vectors and dot products, while in three dimensions it requires eight offset vectors and eight dot products.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] In general, the algorithm has *O*(2*n*) complexity in n dimensions.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] The final step is interpolation between the 2*n* dot products.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Interpolation is performed using a function that has zero first derivative (and possibly also second derivative) at the 2*n* grid nodes.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Therefore, at points close to the grid nodes, the output will approximate the dot product of the gradient vector of the node and the offset vector to the node.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] This means that the noise function will pass through 0 at every node, giving Perlin noise its characteristic look.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Noise functions for use in computer graphics typically produce values in the range [–1.0, 1.0] and can be scaled accordingly.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] In Ken Perlin's original implementation he used a simple hashing scheme to determine what gradient vector is associated with each grid intersection.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] A pre-computed permutation table is used to turn a given grid coordinate into a random number.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] This specific permutation is not absolutely required, though it does require a randomized array of the integers 0 to 255.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] If creating a new permutation table, care should be taken to ensure uniform distribution of the values.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] To get a gradient vector using the permutation table the coordinates of a grid point are looked up sequentially in the permutation table adding the value of each coordinate to the permutation of the previous coordinate.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] The algorithm then looks at the bottom 4 bits of the hash output to pick 1 of 12 gradient vectors for that grid point.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] For each evaluation of the noise function, the dot product of the position and gradient vectors must be evaluated at each node of the containing grid cell.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Perlin noise therefore scales with complexity *O*(2*n*) for n dimensions.
[src:perlin-noise/perlin-noise] Alternatives to Perlin noise producing similar results with improved complexity scaling include simplex noise and OpenSimplex noise.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] Whereas Perlin noise interpolates between the gradients at the surrounding hypergrid end points (i.e., northeast, northwest, southeast and southwest in 2D), simplex noise divides the space into simplices (i.e., n -dimensional triangles).
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] While a hypercube in n dimensions has $2^{n}$ corners, a simplex in n dimensions has only $n+1$ corners.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] The triangles are equilateral in 2D, but in higher dimensions the simplices are only approximately regular.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] For example, the tiling in the 3D case of the function is an orientation of the tetragonal disphenoid honeycomb.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] Simplex noise is useful for computer graphics applications, where noise is usually computed over 2, 3, 4, or possibly 5 dimensions.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] For higher dimensions, *n*-spheres around *n*-simplex corners are not densely enough packed, reducing the support of the function and making it zero in large portions of space.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] Simplex noise is most commonly implemented as a two-, three-, or four-dimensional function, but can be defined for any number of dimensions.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] An implementation typically involves four steps: coordinate skewing, simplicial subdivision, gradient selection, and kernel summation.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] The resulting coordinate (*x*', *y*', ...) is then used in order to determine which skewed unit hypercube cell the input point lies in, (*xb*' = floor(*x*'), *yb*' = floor(*y*'), ...), and its internal coordinates (*xi*' = *x*' − *xb*', *yi*' = *y*' − *yb*', ...).
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] Once the above is determined, the values of the internal coordinate (*xi*', *yi*', ...) are sorted in decreasing order, to determine which skewed Schläfli orthoscheme simplex the point lies in.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] Then the resulting simplex is composed of the vertices corresponding to an ordered edge traversal from (0, 0, ..., 0) to (1, 1, ..., 1), of which there are *n*! possibilities, each of which corresponds to a single permutation of the coordinate.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] In other words, start with the zero coordinate and successively add-ones starting in the value corresponding to the largest internal coordinate's value, ending with the smallest.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] The *yi*' coordinate is the largest, so it is added first.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] It is then followed by the *xi*' coordinate, and finally *zi*'.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] Each simplex vertex is added back to the skewed hypercube's base coordinate and hashed into a pseudo-random gradient direction.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] The hash can be implemented in numerous ways, though most often uses a permutation table or a bit manipulation scheme.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] Care should be taken in the selection of the set of gradients to include, to keep directional artifacts to a minimum.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] The contribution from each of the *n* + 1 vertices of the simplex is factored in by a summation of radially symmetric kernels centered around each vertex.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] This point is subtracted from the input coordinate to obtain the unskewed displacement vector.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] where *r*2 is usually set to either 0.5 or 0.6: the value 0.5 ensures no discontinuities, whereas 0.6 may increase visual quality in applications for which the discontinuities are not noticeable; 0.6 was used in Ken Perlin's original reference implementation.
[src:perlin-noise/simplex-noise] Uses of implementations in *3D and higher* for *textured image synthesis* were covered by U.S. patent 6,867,776, if the algorithm were implemented using the specific techniques described in any of the patent claims, which expired on January 8, 2022.
[src:perlin-noise/value-noise] For many applications, multiple octaves of this noise can be generated and then summed together, just as can be done with Perlin noise and Simplex noise, in order to create a form of fractal noise.
